Good — with `recursive=1` you get all blobs in one call. Then you just need to fetch each blob. So the flow would be:

```
1 API call: GET refs/notes/ai                          → notes commit SHA
1 API call: GET git/commits/<sha>                      → tree SHA
1 API call: GET git/trees/<tree>?recursive=1           → all blob SHAs + commit SHAs (from paths)
N API calls: GET git/blobs/<sha> for each note blob    → attribution JSON
= 3 + N total calls
```

### Option 2: Build a `fetchGitAiNotes()` function

Same architecture as your current `github-checkpoints.ts`, but for git-ai notes:

```typescript
const NOTES_REF = 'refs/notes/ai';

export async function fetchGitAiNotes(
  headers: Record<string, string>
): Promise<Map<string, GitAiNote>> {
  // 1. Get notes ref
  const ref = await fetchWithRetry(
    `${BASE_URL}/repos/${REPO}/git/ref/notes/ai`, headers
  );
  const notesCommitSha = ref.object.sha;

  // 2. Get tree
  const commit = await fetchWithRetry(
    `${BASE_URL}/repos/${REPO}/git/commits/${notesCommitSha}`, headers
  );
  const tree = await fetchWithRetry(
    `${BASE_URL}/repos/${REPO}/git/trees/${commit.tree.sha}?recursive=1`, headers
  );

  // 3. Each blob path = commit SHA (split: "3e/2941c2ca..." → "3e2941c2ca...")
  const notes = new Map<string, GitAiNote>();
  for (const entry of tree.tree) {
    if (entry.type !== 'blob') continue;
    const commitSha = entry.path.replace('/', '');

    // 4. Fetch blob content
    const blob = await fetchWithRetry(
      `${BASE_URL}/repos/${REPO}/git/blobs/${entry.sha}`, headers
    );
    const content = decodeBase64Utf8(blob.content);
    const jsonPart = content.split('---\n')[1];
    if (jsonPart) {
      notes.set(commitSha, JSON.parse(jsonPart));
    }
  }
  return notes;
}
```

### Option 3: CI job exports to a known location

Add a GitHub Action that runs `git-ai` CLI on the server and writes a JSON file to a known branch/artifact — similar to how you currently generate `checkpoints-cache.json`:

```yaml
- run: |
    git-ai fetch-notes
    git-ai prompts --since 90
    git-ai prompts exec "SELECT * FROM prompts" > git-ai-export.json
```

### Recommendation

**Option 2** is the most natural fit — it matches your existing architecture. You'd end up with two data sources in the dashboard:

| Data Source | What It Provides |
|-------------|-----------------|
| `entire/checkpoints/v1` (current) | Tokens, BMAD learnings, summaries, commands |
| `refs/notes/ai` (git-ai) | Line attribution, agent %, model breakdown, accepted/overridden |

Both use the same GitHub API pattern. You could merge them into a single `CheckpointMeta` at fetch time.

